    <segment id="1" parent="8" relname="antithesis">
Intuitiveness incorporates not only a sense of instinct within an interface,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="19" relname="span"> but also defines 
an accelerated learning curve for those areas that users may have particular trouble in.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="20" relname="span">  
I would make a safe wager to propose that there is no program of significant size that is 
100% intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="9" relname="condition">  If there were,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="17" relname="span"> one would only have to look at each feature once and 
know it.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="10" relname="antithesis">  Therefore, not only does intuitiveness include the first instinctive impression, </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="18" relname="span">
but also the process of learning afterwards.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="11" relname="antithesis">  This is not to say that a program should be 
completely juvenile,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="14" relname="span"> but that even advanced features should be intuitive or near-self-
explanatory as possible.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="circumstance">  For instance, when programming in GUI based languages such 
as Visual Basic or Pascal (Delphi).</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="span">  Many features are complex,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="16" relname="span"> but with the help of 
intuitive design of the interfaces, even novice users can pick up on the functionality of 
many advanced functions.</segment>
